{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492910"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:49:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:49:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1183"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1183"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.15,0.13,0.17,0.53]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1183"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53673"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1183","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1183"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1183"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39141"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1200"},{"type":"tags","id":"2943"},{"type":"tags","id":"3526"},{"type":"tags","id":"3791"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5024"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6281"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16027"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42241"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53673"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for follow-up after a recent hospital admission for ureteric colic. During his admission, routine blood tests revealed an elevated serum calcium level of 2.65 mmol/L (2.10-2.60). He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Subsequent investigations show a marginally elevated parathyroid hormone level. Ultrasound examination of the neck is normal. A sestamibi scan suggests a left lower parathyroid adenoma.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance and discharge","CT scan of the neck","Repeat blood investigations in six months","Annual laboratory and imaging follow-up","Referral for parathyroidectomy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with biochemical and imaging evidence of primary hyperparathyroidism, likely due to a parathyroid adenoma. The elevated serum calcium and parathyroid hormone levels, along with the sestamibi scan findings, support this diagnosis. Moreover, the recent episode of ureteric colic suggests symptomatic disease, as nephrolithiasis is a common complication of primary hyperparathyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral for parathyroidectomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step in management for this patient. Parathyroidectomy is the definitive treatment for symptomatic primary hyperparathyroidism. The presence of symptoms (ureteric colic) and the patient\u0027s young age (32 years) make him a clear candidate for surgical intervention. Surgery has a high success rate (90-95%) in improving symptoms and normalizing calcium levels, with minimal complications when performed by experienced surgeons.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance and discharge\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate in this case. While some patients with asymptomatic primary hyperparathyroidism can be managed conservatively, this patient has symptomatic disease and requires definitive treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan of the neck\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated at this stage. The sestamibi scan has already localized the likely parathyroid adenoma, and a CT scan would not change the management plan. It would expose the patient to unnecessary radiation without providing additional benefit.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat blood investigations in six months\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Eannual laboratory and imaging follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E are appropriate strategies for asymptomatic patients with mild primary hyperparathyroidism who do not meet criteria for surgery. However, given this patient\u0027s symptomatic presentation and young age, active intervention rather than monitoring is indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s worth noting that sestamibi scanning is the preferred initial imaging modality for localizing parathyroid adenomas. Ultrasound can also be useful but may miss small adenomas or those in ectopic locations. The combination of biochemical testing and sestamibi scanning provides a high degree of diagnostic accuracy for primary hyperparathyroidism.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Parathyroidectomy is the mainstay treatment for symptomatic primary hyperparathyroidism.","Sestamibi scan is the preferred imaging modality for localizing parathyroid adenomas.","Ureteric colic can be a presenting symptom of primary hyperparathyroidism due to nephrolithiasis."],"references":["Taniegra ED. Hyperparathyroidism. American family physician. 2004 Jan 15;69(2):333-9. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2004/0115/p333.html","Bilezikian JP, Brandi ML, Eastell R, Silverberg SJ, Udelsman R, Marcocci C, Potts Jr JT. Guidelines for the management of asymptomatic primary hyperparathyroidism: summary statement from the Fourth International Workshop. The Journal of Clinical Endocrinology \u0026 Metabolism. 2014 Oct 1;99(10):3561-9. Available at: https://academic.oup.com/jcem/article/99/10/3561/2836336"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39141"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1183"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39141"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-24T19:43:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-24T19:44:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1183"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53673"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at t